y you still are polite and everyone is not touching your baby.We would not recommend an abra boat on the creek with a pushchair. Seems to risky.Malls are a good place to spend your evenings after sunset - there are nice foodcourts with different choices for each night (and you can keep your budget - costs around 25-30 AED/meal)Grab a taxi to any mall (30-40 AED/ride).Carrefour has a lot of babyfood available, and smaller &quot;supermarkets&quot; tend to have some, pampers easily found. We brought our own babymilk from FIN, because there is only babymilk-powder available in the stores.What youd like to bring for a baby:- something that you can use in a taxi for a safe ride- hat &amp; sunglasses for babies- a piece of cloth to put on the pushchair for shade.- flexibility as a midset.	
Jan 2 2009 	Downtown Dubai [the real Dubai?]	I stayed in the Four Points in Al Mankhool from beginning of November to the end of December in 2008.This was my first trip to Dubai on Business and the first trip I spent away from home by myself - away from the family!. Therefore, the hotel needed to meet the criteria of making me feel at home and comfortable. It did this.Upon my middle of the night arrival, the front door staff where very attentive and I was greeted with a warm reception. The check-in was painless [not what I can say for many UK hotels!] and quick and I was soon led to my room on the 7th Floor. My initial impression of the hotel was that it was new and therefore by default, clean and tidy. This turned out to be partially correct: it was not clean and tidy simply because it was new [I believe less than 1 year old], but because of the constant attention by the cleaning staff and I can simply say they were very thorough.The room, was spotlessly clean if a little basic, but the theme was up to date and modern. The bathroom was a little on the small side, but it was was well finished [much better than UK standards] and most importantly: it had great shower!The roof top pool is a reasonable size and was well attended by other guests. I only used it a couple of times as I was out on business every day though! But a good clean pool with decent quality poolside furniture. The view however wasn't great, but due to the hotel location, it was never going to be great in any case.I used the gym just about every day I was there and found it a good size and never too busy [although I used it at night ,so not sure if it was busy during the day]. It has a good range of equipment and again, is very clean. The staff were also very pleasant and attentive. The changing rooms again, very clean and the sauna within the changing rooms, clean and always empty ,which meant that most times it took a bit of time to get a decent heat into it - which wasn't a problem.Included within my rate was the buffet breakfast. If you are a big eater, you will get your moneys worth, but if you don't eat too much [like me], then I feel its a tad expensive at 80 Dirhams [circa £14]. The choice is extensive and everybody will find something they like and plenty of it. The staff are very attentive [as they all are!!] and will bend over backwards to make you feel welcome.I ate out mostly [during the day], but did eat in the hotel as well. There is a deal whereby you can get a buffet style meal in the evening, with your drinks included for 180 Dirhams [circa £32]. There are cheaper deals without the drinks, but the reason I mention the drinks one is because a pint of [poor quality - although I would necessarily blame the hotel for this] European Beer is 32 Dirham [circa £5.50]!! A bit expensive, even if the beer was good. Other hotels in the same area offered a far better selection and cheaper. Although to be fair, I never frequently indulged in any case so it wasn't a problem for me, but if you are on a holiday and you fancy a few drinks in your hotel, you could be dissapointed. The hotel was due to open another 'bar' at the end of November, but at time of my departure, this wasn't yet available, so I cannot say if this had any effect on range and price. I did note that in the evening, the restaurant never appeared too busy and when I did eat in [not from the buffet, but from the Italian menu], I found that the portions a little small for 45 Dirham [circa £8] and a little lacking in..... Italian taste? But tasty enough in their own way always well presented.I made a lot of use of the laundry service and it was always ahead of schedule. If I choose the next day service, I normally always got the laundry back the same day [which I guess is down to how busy they are]. The laundry was always well presented and it scores 10 out of 10 for me. The prices were 20 Dirham [circa £3.50] for a shirt, 30 Dirham [circa £5.50] for trousers, and a dry cleaned suit 85 Dirham [circa £15]. Reasonable value in my opinion.I never opted for the in-room internet [I cannot recall the cost] as I felt that it was expensive [compared to what I would normally pay in the UK - but I think this is more down to the cost of internet provision in the UAE and not a case of the hotel taking advantage]. The wireless service provided for free in the lobby was good, but there was a few times that frustratingly I would continually lose the connection. But on the whole, it was pretty reliable, but it could get very busy in the evenings with a lot of people with laptops - which must be an annoyance to non-business people wishing to use the lobby for relaxation. There were occassions [not me personally] had problems connecting, but the hotel engineer always appeared to be available to assist those with problems.Getting a taxi can be a bit of a hit and a miss. On a Friday, they will fight over you to get a fare, but on a Thursday, be prepared to wait. There is always the option the 'limo' cars waiting outside, but the minimum fare is 80 Dirham and I would suggest you just wait on a normal cab. Bear in mind, that Al Mankhool is not exactly the hub of excitement in Dubai. You'll be spending a fair bit of time in taxis if you want to be at Jumeirah beach, Madinat or the Marina areas. On the plus side you are reasonably close to the Gold Souk [personally I would avoid The New Gold Souk which is a big blue and gold coloured building in walking distance], the airport and the Creek. Walking to the Burjuman Mall takes about 10-15 minutes and a walk along to Spinneys supermarket [further along Mankhool Rd] takes about 5 minutes. There are loads of other shops selling..... tat, I suppose, but you might also get the option to buy fake designer merchandise. Also within 15-20 minute walking distance is Al Karama; another district which specialises in fake designer anything! I personally wouldn't go too late at night - not because I think you'll get mugged, but just because being a northern European, I stick out like a sore thumb and therefore get asked, a lot, if I'm interested in fake designer merchandise. Try the daylight for the Al Karama shopping experience!If you want a more 'earthly' experience of Dubai and not so much glitz and glamour, then Al Mankhool appears to be a reasonable choice. If you are expecting the glitz and glamour, then you'll be using the [very inexpensive - the only thing apart from dodgy designer gear that is inexpensive in Dubai!!!] taxis.All in all, a good all round experience for me of Dubai .The hotel is really very good. Depending on what you want out of Dubai it might not be for you, so choose your location carefully, but if you decide on the Burdubai/Creak area, its a great hotel.The two biggest gripes I have:1. [an indirect fault of the hotel] when in the gym, a certain gym member [non-guest] would come in and change the TV channel regardless of who may be viewing a specific channel at the time to their choice and would continue to 'channel hop'. This, in my view, is plain ignorant and I felt that the staff could have advised the 'member' in question, to consider other people. Just a minor gripe really.2. The single biggest source of annoyance for me, was the smoke alarm in the room, directly above the bed. This had a litle orange light, that would flash every 20 seconds or so [I guess so that they could be seen that they were ready to work if need be]. Not noticable until you switch off the lights to get some sleep, then this little light transforms into a powerful beacon which can only be blotted out by pulling the covers up over your head! That light was responsible for me not getting to sleep and then keeping me awake during the night once it woke me up!! Another minor gripe, but a very frustrating one.	
